parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Log density-dependent mortality coefficient (m²/individual/year)

parameters.description: Log optimal temperature for COTS recruitment (untransformed: ~28.4°C). Below this temperature, larval development and survival decline exponentially. At and above this temperature (up to extreme heat), recruitment is maximized.
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Log optimal temperature for COTS recruitment (°C)

parameters.description: Sensitivity parameter controlling steepness of recruitment decline below optimal temperature. Higher values create sharper decline in cold water. Represents the strong temperature-dependence of COTS larval development rates, which slow dramatically in cooler water (<27°C).
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Steepness of COTS recruitment decline in cold water (°C⁻¹)

parameters.description: Sensitivity parameter controlling steepness of recruitment decline at extreme high temperatures. Lower values mean recruitment is maintained across warm temperatures and only declines gradually at extreme heat (>31°C). Represents the fact that warm water extends larval survival periods and increases food availability, with recruitment only declining at bleaching-level temperatures.
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Steepness of COTS recruitment decline at extreme temperatures (°C⁻¹)

parameters.description: Log of extreme temperature threshold where COTS recruitment begins to decline (untransformed: ~31°C). Represents bleaching-level temperatures where metabolic stress outweighs the benefits of warm water. Below this temperature, recruitment is maintained or enhanced by warm conditions.
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Log extreme temperature threshold for COTS recruitment decline (°C)

parameters.description: Enhancement factor for larval immigration on local recruitment
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Effect multiplier of larval immigration on recruitment

parameters.description: Log threshold for recruitment amplification during outbreaks (untransformed: ~0.5 individuals/m^2/year). Represents the combined larval supply (local + immigration) needed to trigger explosive recruitment. Below this threshold, recruitment is weak; above it, positive feedback drives outbreak dynamics.
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Log recruitment threshold for outbreak initiation (individuals/m²/year)

parameters.description: Hill coefficient controlling steepness of recruitment threshold response. Higher values (3-4) create sharper outbreak transitions, lower values (1-2) create gradual responses. Represents the degree of positive feedback in larval settlement and juvenile survival during favorable conditions.
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Hill coefficient for recruitment amplification (dimensionless)

parameters.description: Relative weighting of external larval immigration versus local reproduction in determining recruitment potential. Values >1 indicate immigration is more important than local reproduction for triggering outbreaks, consistent with GBR observations where upstream larval supply drives downstream outbreaks.
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Relative importance of immigration vs local reproduction (dimensionless)

parameters.description: Strength of coupling between coral availability and recruitment success (0-1). High values mean recruitment requires abundant coral resources (food for settling larvae and juveniles). Represents the ecological reality that COTS outbreaks are facilitated by high coral cover providing food for the growing population.
parameters.enhanced_semantic_description: Coral-recruitment feedback strength (0-1)
